<A NAME = "4"></A>Copyright
LABOR TRENDS via NewsNet
January 15, 1994

REPORTS AND STUDIES BENEFIT COSTS VS. SALARY HIKES

Last week we reported government figures
showing how health care costs are eating into the total
benefits pie. Now the U.S. Chamber of Commerce releases
its latest annual survey that finds the cost of benefits
up 3.8 percent continues to outpace increases in salaries
up only 1.4 percent. As if that wasn't bad enough,
employees' disposable pay in effect went down. According
to CoC, "the average employer's share of medical and
medically related costs per employee remained virtually
unchanged at 10.3 percent of payroll, while the total cost
was up 1 percent....As a result, employees had to pay 9
percent more in 1992 for health care coverage, in addition
to increased deductibles in many firms." Overall benefit
costs varied widely by industry, the Chamber finds, from
slightly more than 30 percent for retailers, banks and
apparel manufacturers, to more than 40 percent for primary
and fabricated metals, machinery, transportation and
rubber industries.



