<A NAME = "5"></A>Copyright
PLATT'S METALS WEEK via NewsNet
January 1, 1996   

KRASNOYARSK FACING LOSSES

The Krasnoyarsk Metallurgical Plant (KraMZ), one of Russia's biggest
processed aluminum producers, could post year-end losses of around
Rb100-bil ($215-mil), a senior company official told the Interfax news
agency. KraMZ financial manager Alexander Bocharov said output in October
and November was down by half on the previous year, resulting in losses of
Rb42-bil by the start of December. The downturn had been caused mainly by
an imbalance between domestic and world prices for primary aluminum,
Bocharov said. Costs inside Russia had soared to $2,500/mt against
$1,600/mt for the London quoted price because of rising electricity, rail
and other charges, he said. In 1994, KraMZ produced 67,660mt of aluminum
ingots and 21,570mt of rolled aluminum products, of which 23.4% and 33.1%
respectively were exported.

Copyright 1996 The McGraw-Hill Companies



