PRINCETON MINING GETS OKAY FOR BC MINE

Canada's Princeton Mining has announced that the development of its
Huckleberry copper and molybdenum mine has been approved by the British
Columbia government. Copper production is forecast to average 65-mil
lb/year during the first five years and total 1-bil lb over the life of the
mine. Molybdenum production is expected to average more than 1-mil lb/year.
The mine will cost $137-mil to develop with construction starting in
January and lasting 18 months. A strategic alliance has been formed by
Princeton with a consortium of Japanese companies--Mitsubishi Materials
Corp, Marubeni Corp, Dowa Mining Co, and Furukawa Co--who will take a 40%
stake, senior finance a $60-mil project loan, and buy the mine's total
copper concentrate production.

